{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596444"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:13:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:13:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15409"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15409"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.19,0.04,0.08,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63896"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8100"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49326"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20722"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63896"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents with a two day history of increasingly severe and generalised abdominal pain. This is on the background of two months of persistent diarrhoea, rectal bleeding and mucorrhoea. On examination her blood pressure is 110/64 mmHg, pulse 96/min and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended, with widespread tenderness. The diagnosis of inflammatory bowel disease is very likely and the challenge is then to distinguish between ulcerative colitis and Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most commonly associated with ulcerative colitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cobblestone mucosa","Non-caseating granulomas","Skip lesions","Transmural inflammation","Toxic megacolon"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of the distinguishing features between ulcerative colitis and Crohn\u0027s disease. The clinical scenario describes a patient with severe ulcerative colitis who may be developing toxic megacolon, a serious complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic megacolon\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe complication of ulcerative colitis characterised by colonic dilatation (\u0026gt;6 cm) and systemic toxicity. It occurs in approximately 5% of severe flares and requires urgent medical attention due to the risk of perforation. Given this patient\u0027s presentation, toxic megacolon may well be the issue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkip lesions\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of Crohn\u0027s disease, where there are areas of normal mucosa between affected segments. In contrast, ulcerative colitis shows continuous inflammation starting from the rectum and extending proximally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-caseating granulomas\u003C/strong\u003E are a histological hallmark of Crohn\u0027s disease. Ulcerative colitis typically shows superficial mucosal inflammation without granulomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECobblestone mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of Crohn\u0027s disease, caused by deep linear ulcers creating a cobblestone appearance. Ulcerative colitis typically shows continuous erythema, friability, and superficial ulceration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransmural inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E affecting all layers of the bowel wall is characteristic of Crohn\u0027s disease. Ulcerative colitis typically only affects the mucosa and submucosa.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Toxic megacolon is a severe complication of ulcerative colitis characterised by colonic dilatation and systemic toxicity.","Ulcerative colitis involves continuous inflammation starting from the rectum, unlike Crohn\u0027s disease which has skip lesions.","Histologically, ulcerative colitis shows superficial mucosal inflammation without granulomas, unlike Crohn\u0027s disease."],"references":["Cai Z, Wang S, Li J. Treatment of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Comprehensive Review. Front Med (Lausanne). 2021 Dec 20;8:765474. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2021.765474. PMID: 34988090; PMCID: PMC8720971","McDowell C, Farooq U, Haseeb M. Inflammatory Bowel Disease. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262182","Fakhoury M, Negrulj R, Mooranian A, Al-Salami H. Inflammatory bowel disease: clinical aspects and treatments. J Inflamm Res. 2014 Jun 23;7:113-20. doi: 10.2147/JIR.S65979. PMID: 25075198; PMCID: PMC4106026","Tavakoli P, Vollmer-Conna U, Hadzi-Pavlovic D, Grimm MC. A Review of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Model of Microbial, Immune and Neuropsychological Integration. Public Health Rev. 2021 May 5;42:1603990. doi: 10.3389/phrs.2021.1603990. PMID: 34692176; PMCID: PMC8386758","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49326"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15409"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"4